label.value: localization phenotype during meiotic cell cycle

value.value: A cell phenotype that affects the localization of a structure or substance in a cell during a meiotic cell cycle.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

label.value: abnormal meiotic spindle localization

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which localization of the meiotic spindle is abnormal during one or both meiotic nuclear divisions.

label.value: normal histone H3-K9 acetylation at subtelomeric heterochromatin during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which acetylation of lysine at position 9 of histone H3 in heterochromatin at subtelomeric regions is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: abnormal iMTOC assembly

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which interphase microtubule organizing center (iMTOC) assembly is abnormal. iMTOC assembly is the aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form an interphase microtubule organizing center.

label.value: cytoplasmic microtubules detached from nuclear envelope

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cytoplasmic microtubules become detached from the nuclear envelope (NE). Normally, some cytoplasmic microtubules are nucleated at the NE and remain attached.

definition.value: This phenotype may result from either absence of the microtubule bundle that would normally attach to the SPB, or from a problem with the SPB-microtubule attachment process.

label.value: abolished protein phosphorylation during cellular response to leucine starvation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the phosphorylation of one or more specific proteins, or of specific protein sites, does not occur during a cellular response to leucine starvation.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal septin ring morphology

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the size, shape, and structure of the septin ring is abnormal.

label.value: increased mitotic DNA replication initiation from inefficient origin

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the frequency of DNA replication initiation is higher than normal at inefficient origins, i.e. replication origins that normally rarely fire.

label.value: decreased cellular dNTP level

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of one or more 2'-deoxyribonucleoside triphosphates (dNTPs) measured in a cell is lower than normal.

label.value: abolished histone H3-K36 trimethylation at promoter during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which trimethylation of lysine at position 36 of histone H3 in one or more promoter regions does not occur.

label.value: abolished histone H3-K36 dimethylation at promoter during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which dimethylation of lysine at position 36 of histone H3 in one or more promoter regions does not occur.

label.value: fragmented spindle pole body

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the spindle pole body is broken into fragments.

label.value: fragmented meiotic spindle pole body

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the meiotic spindle pole body is broken into fragments.

label.value: abnormal spindle pole body morphology during meiotic cell cycle

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which the size, shape, or structure of the spindle pole body is abnormal during the meiotic cell cycle.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal spindle pole body organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in abnormal spindle pole body structure.

label.value: sensitive to nitrosative stress

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to nitrosative stress.

definition.value: Use this term if you have assayed growth of cells exposed to nitrosative stress in culture.

label.value: altered cellular nitric oxide level

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the amount of nitric oxide measured in a cell differs from normal.

label.value: increased cellular nitric oxide level during stationary phase

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the amount of nitric oxide measured in a cell is higher than normal when the population in which the cell is found is in stationary phase.

label.value: decreased cellular nitric oxide level during stationary phase

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the amount of nitric oxide measured in a cell is lower than normal when the population in which the cell is found is in stationary phase.

label.value: abolished histone RNA level oscillation during mitotic cell cycle

value.value: A gene expression phenotype in which the levels of RNAs that encode histones, which normally vary over the course of the mitotic cell cycle, remain constant. All RNAs encoding histones, or one or more specific histone RNA, may be affected.

definition.value: We recommend noting which RNA(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased level of histone gene mRNA during mitotic S phase

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of one or more histone RNAs measured in a cell is lower than normal (i.e. lower than observed in wild-type cells) during S phase of the mitotic cell cycle. Histone RNAs are transcribed from genes encoding histones.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription.

label.value: increased level of histone gene mRNA during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of one or more histone RNAs measured in a cell is higher than normal (i.e. lower than observed in wild-type cells). Histone RNAs are transcribed from genes encoding histones.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription.

label.value: increased level of histone gene mRNA during mitotic interphase

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of one or more histone RNAs measured in a cell is higher than normal (i.e. lower than observed in wild-type cells) during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle. Histone RNAs are transcribed from genes encoding histones.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription.

label.value: overlapping meiosis II spindles

value.value: A spindle phenotype in which the meiotic spindles in adjacent dividing nuclei overlap during meiosis II.

label.value: increased duration of resolution of meiotic recombination intermediates

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the duration of the cleavage and rejoining of intermediates formed during meiotic recombination is longer than normal. All intermediates or a subset (such as a specific type or configuration of intermediate) may remain present for longer than normal.

label.value: normal resolution of meiotic recombination intermediates

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the cleavage and rejoining of intermediates formed during meiotic recombination is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: increased duration of Rad51 focus presence during meiotic cell cycle

value.value: A cell phenotype in which sites at which the protein Rad51 accumulates remain present for longer than normal during the meiotic cell cycle. Normally, Rad51 foci form during prophase I but disappear before metaphase I.

label.value: normal duration of Rad51 focus presence during meiotic cell cycle

value.value: A cell phenotype in which sites at which the protein Rad51 accumulates remain present for a normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) amount of time during the meiotic cell cycle. Normally, Rad51 foci form during prophase I but disappear before metaphase I.

label.value: decreased number of Fbh1 foci during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the number of sites at which the protein Fbh1 (also called Rad22) accumulates is lower than normal.

label.value: increased level of histone gene mRNA during mitotic S phase

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of one or more histone RNAs measured in a cell is higher than normal (i.e. lower than observed in wild-type cells) during S phase of the mitotic cell cycle. Histone RNAs are transcribed from genes encoding histones.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription.

label.value: decreased meiotic sister chromatid cohesion at centromere during meiosis I

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which cohesion between sister chromatids is decreased in centromeric regions during the first meiotic nuclear division.

label.value: abolished meiotic sister chromatid cohesion at centromere during meiosis I

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which cohesion between sister chromatids does not occur in centromeric regions during the first meiotic nuclear division.

label.value: normal meiotic sister chromatid cohesion at centromere during meiosis I

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which cohesion between sister chromatids is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in centromeric regions during the first meiotic nuclear division.

label.value: normal attachment of spindle microtubules to kinetochore during meiosis I

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the attachment of spindle microtubules to the kinetochore during the first meiotic nuclear division is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: abolished attachment of spindle microtubules to kinetochore during meiosis I

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the attachment of spindle microtubules to the kinetochore during the first meiotic nuclear division does not occur.

label.value: normal mitotic sister chromatid biorientation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the stable attachment of sister chromatids to microtubules emanating from opposite poles of the mitotic spindle during metaphase plate congression is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: normal histone H3-K9 dimethylation at subtelomeric heterochromatin during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the dimethylation of lysine at position 9 of histone H3 in subtelomeric regions is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: inviable mononucleate vegetative cell

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell is inviable, and contains a single nucleus.

label.value: enlarged mitotic spindle pole body

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the mitotic spindle pole body is larger than normal.

label.value: normal vesicle-mediated transport during vegetative growth

value.value: A transport phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which vesicle-mediated transport is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: This term can be used for protein transport or for the movement of other substances (e.g. lipids or ions) via vesicles. If it is used for a protein transport phenotype, we recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay.

label.value: abnormal tubular endoplasmic reticulum morphology

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the size, shape, or structure of the tubular endoplasmic reticulum (ER) is abnormal. The tubular ER is the portion of the ER that consists of tubules having membranes with high curvature in cross-section.

label.value: decreased protein localization to medial cortical node, with protein distributed in cell cortex, during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the medial cortical node of a cell is decreased, and the protein is instead detected distributed throughout the cell cortex. There may be little or no protein detected at the medial cortical node.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased FAD binding

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which occurrence of FAD binding by a gene product (usually a protein) in a mutant is increased. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

definition.value: This term can mean that the mutated gene product itself binds FAD more than wild type, or that a mutation in one gene increases FAD binding by a second gene product. When using this term, it is therefore recommended to note the specific protein(s) affected.

label.value: abnormal S-phase DNA damage checkpoint during cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate

value.value: A cell cycle checkpoint phenotype in which the S-phase DNA damage checkpoint (also known as the intra-S phase DNA damage checkpoint) is abnormal when the cell is exposed to methyl methanesulfonate. The S phase DNA damage checkpoint slows progression through S phase in response to DNA damage.

label.value: normal mitotic DNA damage checkpoint during cellular response to methyl methanesulfonate

value.value: A cell cycle checkpoint phenotype in which the mitotic DNA damage checkpoint is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) when the cell is exposed to methyl methanesulfonate. The S phase DNA damage checkpoint slows progression through S phase in response to DNA damage.

label.value: alkylation damage repair intermediates absent

value.value: A cell phenotype in which DNA molecules corresponding to alkylation damage repair intermediates are absent from the cell during DNA replication.

label.value: increased level of X-shaped replication intermediates

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the level of X-shaped DNA replication intermediates is greater than normal. X-shaped intermediates may be formed by replication forks moving bidirectionally from outside the region, or by the increased formation or persistence of Holliday junctions or similar recombination intermediates.

label.value: abolished protein kinase activity during cellular response to hydroxyurea

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which a protein kinase activity is absent during a cellular response to hydroxyurea.

label.value: increased protein kinase activity during cellular response to hydroxyurea

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of a protein kinase activity is increased during a cellular response to hydroxyurea.

label.value: constitutively activated sterol regulatory element binding protein cleavage

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the proteolytic processing of sterol regulatory element binding protein (SREBP) into its transcriptionally active form is activated continuously. Normally, SREBP is cleaved only in response to altered levels of one or more lipids.

label.value: decreased transcription of amino acid biosynthesis genes

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which transcription of amino acid biosynthesis genes from RNA polymerase II promoters occurs to a lower extent than normal. Amino acid biosynthesis genes are those whose products are involved in amino acid biosynthetic processes.
